media.description:
This is an extra 3D printed teeth from this:
https://picasaweb.google.com/102303773171415008577/1309013DPrintedScarryCactus?authuser=0&feat=directlink

Let's try to electroplate it with copper.
media.title: 20150718_104555.jpg

media.description: Drill a hole for a screw to hold it and make the primary electrical connection.
media.title: 20150718_104640.jpg

media.description: Screw installed
media.title: 20150718_104749.jpg

media.description: The surface needs to be conductive to electroplate it, so I am going to cover it with graphite lubricant.
media.title: 20150718_104828.jpg

media.description: The lubricant goes on wet with some volatile fluid to hold the graphite in suspension I think.
media.title: 20150718_105119.jpg

media.description:
The fluid evaporates quickly and leaves a dark grey matte finish.  I applied 2 coats.

Note, others have baked their parts at low temperatures for hours to create a good conductive shell.  I however, am not that patient, applied two coats of graphite lubricant and as soon as it looked dry started to play.
media.title: 20150718_105210.jpg

media.description: While waiting for the coats of graphite lubricant to set up, I got some of the chemistry set up and cleaned some coins and aluminum pieces for plating.
media.title: 20150718_105454.jpg

media.description: I tried Tarn-X, soapy water, water, and ammonia.
media.title: 20150718_105459.jpg

media.description: ...with paper towels, towels, scrubbies, and wire brushes.
media.title: 20150718_105509.jpg

media.description: Getting set up for plating.  3V C cell battery power supply with anode (+) through ammeter to well sanded copper tubing - our copper doner for the day.  Copper saturated used PCB etchant warming up in hot water bath.
media.title: 20150718_105516.jpg

media.description: Hot water bath just over 110 degrees f.
media.title: 20150718_105552.jpg

media.description: The graphite coating is nearly dry.
media.title: 20150718_105738.jpg

media.description: Copper plated nickel.  This plating happened in seconds.
media.title: 20150718_114536.jpg

media.description: Copper plated nickel compared to non plated nickel.
media.title: 20150718_114545.jpg

media.description:
Warmed copper saturated sodium per sulfate solution poured into glass jar and copper anode inserted.  

Note: The sodium per sulfate is a nasty acid and I treat it very carefully; the fluid on the bench to the right and dampening the paper towel is just water that dripped off the outside of the container from the hot bath and NOT the acid etchant itself.
media.title: 20150718_115100.jpg

media.description: Using a wire brush to de-oxidize and brighten the end of a piece of extruded aluminum.  The quality of any plating is dependent on the preparation of the surface to be plated.
media.title: 20150718_115341.jpg

media.description: Sanding the end of the aluminum to be plated.
media.title: 20150718_115418.jpg

media.description: Ready to start
media.title: 20150718_115829.jpg

media.description: Starting to react, note the dark edges.
media.title: 20150718_120032.jpg

media.description: 450ma, a respectable current.
media.title: 20150718_120053.jpg

media.description: It's hard to see in the blue tinted acid, but when brought near the glass jar you can clearly see the pinkish hue of a fresh copper coating.
media.title: 20150718_120239.jpg

media.description: Good copper coating, it looks rough but that's how the copper deposits on copper.
media.title: 20150718_120852.jpg

media.description: Note the anodized outer surface did not plate and remains the original dull silver color.
media.title: 20150718_120911.jpg

media.description:
How it looks after a rinse.

The clip lead is also plated now.
media.title: 20150718_121803.jpg

media.description: Time to start trying to plate the graphite coated PLA.  Electrical and mechanical connection is made to the screw.
media.title: 20150718_121916.jpg

media.description: 150ma to start, and that is probably coating the screw more than anything else.
media.title: 20150718_121934.jpg

media.description: A pinkish copper hue is observed along the bottom back edge of the part.  This is very encouraging!
media.title: 20150718_122534.jpg

media.description: Current increased back to 450ma, coating is occurring.
media.title: 20150718_122543.jpg

media.description:
As you can see here, the screw was getting most of the coating.  
We switched to the higher voltage and current capability of a car battery charger, 12v up to 4a.
We tried suspending the part higher, forcing the coating to occur on the part and it was slow but successful as you can see by the copper line on this part.
media.title: 20150718_124747.jpg

media.description: Watching the process at 12v 30ma.
media.title: 20150718_124754.jpg

media.description:
Some action!
A copper coating started spreading over the part.  Lots of bubbles are produced at the edges.  Nice to see the coating spreading and not just plating in one place.
media.title: 20150718_125043.jpg

media.description: Copper plating and bubbles visible
media.title: 20150718_125056.jpg

media.description: 1.5a-2a and you can see the bubbles from the reaction.
media.title: 20150718_125326.mp4

media.description: Copper spreading over the part, but building up thick on places where hit has coated already and on the screw.  We're not sure how to get a good coating without ending up with a lumpy ball of copper.
media.title: 20150718_125513.jpg

media.description: Submerged the part so that the screw is not in the acid.  This is the distance between the copper donating anode on the right and the part on the left.
media.title: 20150718_132841.jpg

media.description: Back to batteries at 370ma.
media.title: 20150718_141245.jpg

media.description: Lumpiness is copper coating, and bubbles are trapped below the part, inhibiting coating there.
media.title: 20150718_141307.jpg

media.description: Lumpiness is copper coating, and bubbles are trapped below the part, inhibiting coating there.
media.title: 20150718_141312.jpg

media.description: Added a battery, as the original 2 were getting tired, propped up the jar, running at 440ma.
media.title: 20150718_145801.jpg

media.description: Close up of the copper deposition, notice how it is mounding up in the back.  The copper is plating to copper where the conductance is highest, not to the rest of the graphite coated part.
media.title: 20150718_145845.jpg

media.description:
The copper started to coat the back but then copper preferred to plate copper rather than the graphite coating.
The ridges are in the original part and are from the 3D printing.
media.title: 20150718_145909.jpg

media.description:
A rinsed peek at the coating.
Pieces easily chip away as can be seen on the right side of the part.
media.title: 20150718_150152.jpg

media.description: Continuing to plate.
media.title: 20150718_154147.jpg

media.description: Plating
media.title: 20150718_154200.jpg

media.description:
Three hours later on battery power...
The copper tube anode has broken off and fallen to the bottom of the jar, and the blue tint indicating copper content from the acid has striated making the bottom deep blue and the top much clearer.
media.title: 20150718_191231.jpg

media.description: Much more of the part managed to plate with copper.
media.title: 20150718_191237.jpg

media.description: Inserted the anode deeper into the acid, here you can more clearly see the variation in copper content.  There is a lot of debris in suspension and on the bottom, I think much of it is from hard water deposits inside the copper tubing and other impurities.
media.title: 20150718_191436.jpg

media.description: Down to 50ma.  The batteries are probably worn out, there is less anode surface area, and we're up to a part of the copper tube that had not been sanded and prepped as well as the bottom.
media.title: 20150719_153952.jpg

media.description: Final copper coating.
media.title: 20150719_154121.jpg

media.description: Final copper coating.
media.title: 20150719_154131.jpg

media.description: Final copper coating.
media.title: 20150719_154136.jpg

media.description: Final copper coating.
media.title: 20150719_154142.jpg

media.description: Final copper coating.
media.title: 20150719_154154.jpg

media.description: Final anode condition.  It not only etched through, but he bottom black portion is tissue paper thin.
media.title: 20150719_154303.jpg

media.description: Final anode condition.  It not only etched through, but he bottom black portion is tissue paper thin.
media.title: 20150719_154313.jpg

media.description:
Filtering the debris and dispensing the used etchant back into the plastic bottle.
I don't know what chemical condition the stuff ended up in.
The debris appears to be copperish.
media.title: 20150719_154509.jpg

media.description: Let's try to buff up the part
media.title: 20150801_155304.jpg

media.description:
After some time with the steel brush on the Dremmel.

Note during this process I started to taste copper.  This is a very bad sign so I stopped, cleaned up, ventilated, and returned later working with airflow from behind me and nitrile gloves.
media.title: 20150801_155934.jpg

media.description: Some areas cleaned up with a nice copper plate, others quickly wore through to the graphite.
media.title: 20150801_155939.jpg

media.description: The copper stayed where the plating was thin, but where the copper built up it occasionally peeled away all the way down to the graphite.
media.title: 20150801_155944.jpg

media.description: Sorry it's so blurry but it's the only view of the finished bottom.
media.title: 20150801_155952.jpg
